{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LTHrWhNvJaXvyQMk9UCVCA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The certificate has SANs:\n- `DNS:localhost`\n- `DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc`\n- `DNS:*.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`\n\nSo the cert covers `*.elasticsearch.svc` which would match `es-http.elasticsearch.svc`. The service name `es-http` accessed from within the cluster through `es-http:9200` would use the DNS `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`.\n\nBut the curl command uses `https://es-http:9200` which would resolve `es-http` in the `elasticsearch` namespace DNS. The full DNS name would be `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` which is NOT matched by `*.elasticsearch.svc` (wildcard only covers one level).\nActually, wait—`*.elasticsearch.svc` does match `es-http.elasticsearch.svc`. The issue is that Kubernetes DNS search domains would resolve `es-http` to `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, but the TLS SNI that curl sends might be using a different name depending on how the resolution happens.\n\nLet me think about whether the CA certificate in the secret actually signs the TLS certificate—that could be the real problem here.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1035,"cache_read_input_tokens":42881,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1035},"output_tokens":51,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0891e5be-780e-4a01-94d3-f3e382736a57","uuid":"895095d9-f224-4594-8498-d314df80f2f0","request_id":"req_011CcQ2jBi1rHR3twzkJoptU"}
